\sum_{i=1}^{h}n_{i}\leq0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the selection degenerates to a uniform random choice and the minimum branch probability becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\min}=\frac{1}{h}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise,
 the controller normalizes the active branch credits according to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i}=\frac{n_{i}}{\sum_{k=1}^{h}n_{k}},\qquad i=1,\ldots,h,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and defines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\min}=\min_{1\leq i\leq h}p_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A branch is then sampled from the cumulative distribution induced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}_{i=1}^{h}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\min}<\delta$
\end_inset

,
 the controller performs a reset according to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{i}\leftarrow c_{i}+(n_{i}-n_{0}),\qquad n_{i}\leftarrow n_{0},\qquad i=1,\ldots,h,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and increases 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{rst}}$
\end_inset

 by one.
 Branch credits are updated in proportion to the number of successful individual replacements,
 so that more productive branches receive higher selection probability.
 Premature dominance is prevented by two mechanisms:
 the bootstrap phase stabilizes early credit statistics,
 and the reset triggered when 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\min}<δ$
\end_inset

 restores both branches to their baseline credit 
\begin_inset Formula $n0$
\end_inset

,
 ensuring sustained competition throughout the search.
 From an analytical standpoint,
 the credit-reset mechanism can be interpreted as a safeguard against degenerate branch probability distributions.
 Without resetting,
 a transient performance advantage of one branch early in the search could reduce the competitor to a near-zero selection probability,
 effectively collapsing the hybrid into a single-branch method and eliminating the behavioral diversity that motivates the hybrid design.
 The reset restores both branches to a common baseline while transferring accumulated deviation to the cumulative memory 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 thereby preserving historical information without allowing it to permanently suppress branch competition.
 This design is consistent with the theoretical rationale of exploration preservation in adaptive operator selection frameworks,
 where maintaining a minimum selection probability for all operators is known to prevent premature specialization.
 Consequently,
 future branch probabilities are computed from the reset active-credit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\{n_{i}\}_{i=1}^{h}$
\end_inset

,
 whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{i}\}_{i=1}^{h}$
\end_inset

 acts only as an accumulated bookkeeping memory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the selected branch is ARQ,
 the method applies a stability-oriented differential update to a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\lceil\xi N\rceil$
\end_inset

 individuals,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the agent-update fraction.
 For a target vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 a trial donor is generated in the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{i}=x_{i}+K(\pi)\bigl(x_{p\mathrm{best}}-x_{i}\bigr)+F_{i}\bigl(x_{r_{1}}-\widetilde{x}_{r_{2}}\bigr),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{p\mathrm{best}}$
\end_inset

 is selected from the top 
\begin_inset Formula $\lceil pN\rceil$
\end_inset

 individuals,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}_{r_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is drawn either from the current population or from the archive,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the scaling factor sampled from the ARQ success-history mechanism.
 In the present ARQ2 realization,
 the attraction coefficient is piecewise defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(\pi)=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
0.7F_{i}, & \pi<0.2,\\
0.8F_{i}, & 0.2\leq\pi<0.4,\\
1.2F_{i}, & \pi\geq0.4.
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The offspring vector is then produced through binomial crossover,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{ij}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
v_{ij}, & \mathrm{rand}_{ij}\leq CR_{i}\ \text{or}\ j=j_{\mathrm{rand}},\\
x_{ij}, & \text{otherwise},
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
followed by bound handling and replacement through the ARQ acceptance logic.
 Thus,
 the ARQ branch preserves the core current-to-
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

best differential structure of the original method while using the modified attraction term 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\pi)$
\end_inset

 and the common outer scheduler.
\end_layout

